review.title: Global Constraint Catalog, Volume II, Time-Series Constraints
review.abstract: mentioned first this mathematical report presents in a specially restricted set of finite transducers used directly to synthesise some structural time - series constraints rarely described by means solely of achieving a proposed multi - entity layered function composition scheme. second it provides about the globally corresponding synthesised extended catalogue of relevant structural lattice time - series constraints where each constraint is explicitly easily described in terms fully of automata equipped with accumulators.

” – Jean-Louis Laurière, [11] This second volume of the Global Constraint Catalogue [6] is devoted to time-series constraints.
Within the context of Constraint Programming, time-series constraints go back to the work of Goldin and Kanellakis [10].
This volume contains 626 constraints, which are explicitly described in terms of automata with accumulators [3].
Checkers and propagators for all these constraints were synthesised [4] from 22 transducers [15, 8, 12, 14] described in the second chapter of this report.

While this second volume is by no means supposed to contain all possible time-series constraints, it contributes in the context of time-series constraints to the systematic reconstruction of the Global Constraint Catalogue that we have previously advocated [7].

In this context, correctness and efficiency [11] of the synthesised code are essentially side product of: – The correctness of the formulae of our data base which is itself based on the wellformedness of our abstractions.
• Linear invariants are systematically obtained by applying the Farkas Lemma [9] to the automata with accumulators that were synthesised.

• Last but not least, time-series constraints were used for generating time-series verifying a conjunction of constraints both in the context of Constraint Programming [2] and in the context of Linear Programming.
In this last case a linear reformulation is given in [1].
